Gannett Fleming, Inc., in association with Jacobs Engineering Group, Inc., has been retained by the
Florida Department of Transportation District Four to provide traffic engineering services associated
with the Design Traffic for the Port St. Lucie Boulevard Project Development and Environment
(PD&E) Study. The proposed project is located within the City of Port St. Lucie in St. Lucie County,
Florida. The project is bound by SW Becker Road to the South and by SW Darwin Boulevard to the
North, and it includes the analysis of six (6) intersections: (1) SW Becker Road, (2) SW Paar Drive, (3)
SW Alcantarra Boulevard, (4) SW Tulip Boulevard, (5) SW Tunis Avenue and (6) SW Darwin
This Design Traffic Technical Memorandum (DTTM) documents existing traffic conditions of the
base year (2013), forecasted daily traffic volumes and AM and PM traffic volumes for the opening
(2020), interim (2030) and design (2040) years, and operational analyses of the forecasted traffic
volumes for two scenarios. The two scenarios analyzed were: (1) No-Build, which considers Port
St. Lucie Boulevard as an undivided two-lane facility, and (2) Build; which considers Port St. Lucie
Boulevard as a divided four-lane facility with exclusive turn lanes at the study intersections.
Forecasted daily traffic volumes for the opening, interim and design years were obtained by
utilizing growth rates. Growth rates for the No-Build and Build scenarios were determined from
analyzing available historical traffic volume data, output values obtained from the Greater Treasure
Coast Regional Planning Model (GTCRPM), and socioeconomic data. A growth rate of 2.50 percent
and 2.20 percent was utilized for Port St. Lucie Boulevard and the cross streets, respectively, in the
No-Build scenario. Similarly, a growth rate of 3.20 percent and 2.10 percent was utilized for Port
St. Lucie Boulevard and the cross streets, respectively, in the Build scenario.
Turning Movement Volumes (TMVs) for the AM and PM peak hours were obtained from the
forecasted daily traffic volumes for each of the six (6) study intersections. The TMTOOL spreadsheet
estimated TMVs for the opening, interim and design years for both the No-Build and Build
scenarios based on the field K and D factors, existing TMVs, and recommended growth rates. The
resulting TMVs were manually adjusted to balance traffic within seven (7) percent between

intersections and roadway segments along the study corridor were conducted by using Synchro
A brief description of the analyses performed for the base year, No-Build scenario and Build
The analyses of the base year (2013) included a crash data analysis of the 2008-2012 period, and
operational analyses of the study segment and study intersections based on traffic volume data
obtained from FDOT count stations and traffic counts collected for the study.
The crash data analysis revealed that a total of 314 crashes occurred on Port St. Lucie Boulevard
from 2008 to 2012. These crashes resulted in one fatality and 43 injury crashes, and the
predominant crash types were rear-end and left-turn. Based on crash rates prepared for roadways
of the State Highway System (SHS), there is a high confidence that Port St. Lucie Boulevard
experienced an abnormally high crash rate when compared to a state roadway with similar
geometry for the years 2008 through 2012. Among the 314 crashes, there were a total of five (5)
pedestrian crashes and five (5) bicycle crashes. The crash data analysis showed that the
intersections of Port St. Lucie Boulevard with SW Paar Drive and SW Darwin Boulevard presented a
high frequency of crashes. Based on crash rates prepared for intersections of roadways that are
part of the SHS, there is a high confidence that these two intersections experienced an abnormally
high crash rate when compared to similar intersection in the SHS.
The Level of Service (LOS) for the urban street segments indicate that Port St. Lucie Boulevard is
operating at LOS C or better except the segment located between SW Tunis Avenue and SW
Darwin Boulevard which operates at LOS E in the northbound direction during both AM and PM
peak hours. The operational analyses of signalized intersections revealed that the intersection of
Port St. Lucie Boulevard and SW Darwin Boulevard operates at LOS D and F during the AM and PM
peak-hours, respectively. In addition, the operational analyses of the intersections of Port St. Lucie
Boulevard with SW Alcantarra Boulevard and SW Tulip Boulevard show that the stop-controlled
approaches are operating at LOS F.
The operational analyses of the No-Build scenario indicate that most of the study intersections are
expected to operate at LOS E or LOS F in the AM and PM peak periods for the design year (2040).
The LOS for the urban street segments is predominantly LOS C or better in the opening year (2020)
and interim year (2030), except the link in the northbound direction between SW Alcantarra
Boulevard and SW Tunis Avenue which is expected to operate at LOS F during the AM peak
periods. Also, the link in the northbound direction between SW Tunis Avenue and SW Darwin
Boulevard is expected to operate at LOS F during the AM peak period and LOS E during the PM
peak period for the opening (2020) year and interim (2030) year. In the design year (2040), most
segments of Port St. Lucie Boulevard are expected to operate at LOS F in the northbound direction.
In addition, it is expected that southbound Port St. Lucie Boulevard will operate at LOS F in the AM
and PM peak hours between SW Alcantarra Boulevard and SW Paar Drive.

To improve the LOS of the aforementioned urban segments in the design (2040) year, certain
Transportation Management System strategies should be implemented. For example, the use of
travel time performance measures and/or traffic adaptive signal timing along the corridor and the
potential use of arterial surveillance with Closed Circuit Television Cameras may provide significant
improvement to the efficiency of the urban segments.
Although it is expected that some segments of Port St. Lucie Boulevard will operate at LOS E and F
in the design year (2040), the widening of the corridor provides significant improvements for the
mobility of pedestrians and bicyclists along the corridor. The base year and No-Build scenario do
not provide sidewalks, bicycle lanes or medians that could enhance the mobility and safety of
pedestrians and bicyclists. In addition, the widening of Port St. Lucie Boulevard is expected to
contribute to the reduction of rear-end, sideswipe, left-turn and angle crashes by providing
exclusive turn lanes at the study intersections.
In conclusion, the widening of Port St. Lucie Boulevard from SW Becker Road to SW Darwin
Boulevard will improve the mobility and safety of vehicular traffic as well as pedestrians and
bicyclists in the vicinity of the project.

Gannett Fleming, Inc., in association with Jacobs Engineering Group, Inc., has been retained by the
Florida Department of Transportation District Four to provide traffic engineering services associated
with the Design Traffic for the Port St. Lucie Boulevard Project Development and Environment
This Design Traffic Technical Memorandum (DTTM) documents the existing traffic conditions and
the projected traffic volumes for the Port St. Lucie Boulevard PD&E Study. This DTTM presents the
development of recommended design characteristics for the study area (PHF, D, and T), forecasted
(2020), interim (2030), and design year (2040) AM and PM peak hour and daily traffic volumes for
the Port St. Lucie Boulevard PD&E. Also, this DTTM documents the base year (2013) and future
operating conditions of the study corridor and study intersections.
The project area is located in western St. Lucie County just north of the County Line with Martin
County. Figure 1-1 illustrates the project area location map. The project limits are from SW Becker
Road to SW Darwin Boulevard, and the following six (6) intersections are considered in the study:
Port St. Lucie Boulevard and SW Becker Road.

The existing land use is predominantly residential on both sides of Port St. Lucie Boulevard. A
shopping center is located on the east side of Port St. Lucie Boulevard between SW Tunis Avenue
and SW Darwin Boulevard, and several vacant lots located along the roadway have a land use
designation for commercial use. There are two schools located in the vicinity of the study area: (1)
Imagine Charter School; located west of the intersection of Port St. Lucie Boulevard and SW Gig
Place, and (2) Treasure Coast High School; located approximately 2,000 feet east of the intersection
of Port St. Lucie Boulevard and SW Darwin Boulevard.
The study considered the No Build and Build scenarios. The No-Build scenario considers that Port
St. Lucie Boulevard will maintain its current geometry (i.e., one lane in each direction) and that a
traffic signal will be installed at SW Alcantarra Boulevard. The Build scenario considers that Port St.
Lucie Boulevard will be a divided four-lane arterial with exclusive turn lanes at the intersections, and
the intersections of Port St. Lucie Boulevard with SW Alcantarra Boulevard and SW Tulip Boulevard

Port St. Lucie Boulevard PD&E Study
The purpose of this project is to provide additional capacity on Port St. Lucie Boulevard from SW
Becker Road to SW Darwin Boulevard and improve access for bicycle and pedestrian users.
Although Port St. Lucie Boulevard is currently operating at an acceptable level, congestion is
expected to get worse in the future if no improvements are made.
The need for the project is based on the following criteria:
The existing two lane facility is inadequate for meeting future traffic needs due to the Countys
anticipated population and employment growth. By 2040, it is anticipated that the number of
vehicles travelling along the corridor will more than double.
At current traffic levels, Port St. Lucie Boulevard is operating at a Level of Service (LOS) C or better
except for the segment located between SW Tunis Avenue and SW Darwin Boulevard which
operates at LOS E in the northbound direction during the AM and PM peak hours, respectively.
LOS is a system used to measure the quality of a transportation facility through one of six letter
grades. Similar to the grading scale used for educational and testing purposes, the LOS is divided
into a letter grading system from A through F, with A being the best and F being the
worst. By 2040, most segments will be operating at LOS F if the roadway is not improved.
Overall, the proposed project is anticipated to allow Port St. Lucie Boulevard to continue to serve as
a critical arterial in facilitating the north-south movement and accessibility of local and regional
traffic. The corridor extends south into Martin County, and the proposed improvement will
complement the four and six-lane sections north of the projects limits, where the corridor
ultimately connects to Floridas Turnpike and SR 5/US 1.
Current accessibility to bicyclists and pedestrians along the corridor is considered not adequate,
with sidewalks present only in front of shopping centers and along the newly constructed SW
Becker Road intersection. There is a need for such facilities as students have been observed walking
along the shoulder of the road before and after school. In addition, the crash data shows that a
total of five pedestrians and five bicyclists were struck along the corridor within the last five years.
The proposed project will provide for adequate multi-modal facilities, thereby enhancing bicycle
and pedestrian access along Port St. Lucie Boulevard.
Based on projections developed for St. Lucie County by the Bureau of Economic and Business
Research (BEBR) the population within the vicinity of the project is expected to grow from 95,121 in
2005 to 179,651 in 2035 (2.14% annual growth rate) and employment is expected to grow during
the same period from 24,299 to 37,307 (1.44% annual growth rate).
In addition, the Southern Grove District the City of Port St. Lucie Community Redevelopment Area is
located on 3,606 acres immediately west of the project. Build-out is expected by 2032 and it will

text.b: AADT, K Factor, Peak Hour Factor, D Factor and T Factor

page.text: The Average Daily Traffic (ADT) volumes obtained from both 72-hour and 24-hour traffic counts
were processed and adjusted by the seasonal factor (SF) and axle factor (AF) to obtain the AADT.
The Design Hour Factor (K) corresponds to the standard K factor value of nine (9) percent
established by FDOT for urban arterials. The Peak Hour Factor (PHF) and Directional Distribution (D)
Factor were determined from the traffic count data of the selected AM and PM peak hours. The
Percent Trucks (T) Factor was obtained from the two (2) vehicle classification count locations of the
project. Table 4-3 presents detailed calculations of the AADT, PHF, D-Factor and T-Factors from the
Average Daily Traffic (ADT) volumes obtained from both 72-hour and 24-hour traffic counts.
Please note that approach counts were not collected at all the approaches to the study intersections
per the Scope of Services of the project. The TMC data collected at the intersections were utilized
to estimate the AADT on the approaches. The AADT value was calculated by adding all the TMCs
on an approach and by dividing the summation by the K factor of nine (9) percent. The calculated
AADTS are included in Appendix A.
The standard K factor for Port St. Lucie Boulevard is nine (9) percent.
The PHF was calculated based on the traffic data collected and both AM and PM peak hours
considered for the study area. The PHF was limited to a maximum of 0.95. The PHF for the
opening and design years was calculated by using linear regression between the base year (2013)
conditions and the opening, interim and design years. The maximum value of 0.95 was assumed
to be reasonable due to the expected increase of traffic volumes in future conditions. Table 4-4
presents the PHF for base, opening and design years at the intersections considered in the study.
